1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Every engineering team has a memory problem.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:10,000
The fix for last quarter's incident lives in a closed ticket, a Slack thread, or someone's head.

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:17,000
And half of that tribal knowledge is stale — the workaround everyone remembers was replaced two releases ago.

4
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:21,000
PatchPilot is incident memory that never goes stale.

5
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:27,000
It's built end-to-end on Cognee's memory lifecycle — remember, recall, improve, forget —

6
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:32,000
and you're about to watch every one of those four verbs work, live.

7
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Sign-up and sign-in are real — Clerk auth with email or OAuth.

8
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:42,000
I'll sign in with GitHub — and that choice is about to matter,

9
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
because PatchPilot treats your repo as a memory source, not just a login.

10
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:55,000
This is remember. My GitHub username came from the sign-in — I pick a repo, hit Sync Now,

11
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:03,000
and its real issues become incident memory — each one through Cognee's add and cognify, into a knowledge graph.

12
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:10,000
And sync is incremental: next click only pulls issues opened since this one. Continuous memory, not a one-time import.

13
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Now the on-call moment: users aren't getting password-reset emails.

14
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:22,000
I search — and PatchPilot recalls the incident with a recommendation, a real confidence score,

15
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:29,000
and the exact evidence chunks it's grounded in — graph search fused with chunk-level evidence.

16
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Note the answer: run the flush_mail_queue script. That was the right fix… in version 1.8.

17
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Then release one-point-nine ships, migrating email to the SendGrid API. I upload the release note —

18
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:49,000
and watch the old workaround. PatchPilot flagged it red — drifting —

19
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:54,000
with a reason generated live from the new release's knowledge graph.

20
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:00,000
In the memory graph, that red cluster is the stale knowledge, isolated in its own dataset.

21
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Stale memory doesn't get archived — it gets forgotten. One click, Cognee's surgical forget, that dataset only.

22
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Same search, seconds later — the answer has flipped to the current fix. The durable incident history survived untouched.

23
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:25,000
I accept the fix, and improve reinforces it — the next recall ranks it even higher.

24
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:31,000
There's even a conversational layer — same memory, session-aware follow-ups.

25
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:38,000
And the operations feed shows everything you just watched, as lifecycle events:

26
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:45,000
remembered, recalled, drift caught, forgotten, reinforced. The memory is alive — you can see it think.

27
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Remember, recall, improve, forget — every lifecycle verb load-bearing, self-hosted on the open-source stack:

28
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:57,000
Kuzu, LanceDB, SQLite. The whole loop runs in twenty seconds.

29
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:00,000
PatchPilot — every bug remembers its history.
